<h1>Problem 1242 - 2017 Balkan MO, P3 of 4, AN</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(\mathbb{N}\) denote the set of positive integers. Find all functions \(f:\mathbb{N}\rightarrow\mathbb{N}\) such that
\[n+f(m)\mid f(n)+nf(m)\]for all \(m,n\in \mathbb{N}\).</p>
<h2>Thinking</h2>
<div class='skib'>
<p>We'll use Euclid, which gives \(n+f(m) \mid f(n) - n^2\). We would love to vary \(m\) and say that \(f(n) - n^2 = 0\) but that only works if \(f(m)\) is unbounded.</p>
<p>So suppose \(f(m)\) is bounded. Then \(f(n) \equiv n^2 \equiv f(m)^2 \pmod{n+f(m)}\). Since we can vary \(n\) to make \(n + f(m)\) very large and \(f(x)\) (thus \(f(x)^2\)) is bounded, we get \(f(n) = f(m)^2\) for all \(n\), \(m\). This means \(f(n) = 1 \; \forall n\), which is a working solution. </p>
<p>Now suppose \(f\) is unbounded, which would give from the first paragraph that we can vary \(m\) to make \(f(m)\) big - this means \(f(n) = n^2 \; \forall n\), also a working solution. </p>
</div>
<h2>Idea</h2>
<p>Euclid overpowers divisibility-adjacent FEs.</p>
